{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1552289632,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQzNTM4NTY4Mg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-435385682"},"message":"Hmm, never taught of that. Mostly we hash strings not ints, so they are pointers. But if you come up with some tests, we would be very pleased of course.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1552289632,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDE5NDQ5OTEyOA=="},"target":"c4d9994143dd0e888222560c59775ed8be08a7216bedf043d7e643d4e4699db8","message":"Hmm, never thought of that. Mostly we hash strings not ints, so they are pointers. But if you come up with some tests, we would be very pleased of course.","files":null},{"type":5,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1552737611,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOkxhYmVsZWRFdmVudDIyMDgxMzU3NTk="},"added":["enhancement"],"removed":[]},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"af50ed18e547bb30a17e59ab9463f126d8b41990"},"timestamp":1587636019,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDYxODMwNzI3Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-618307276"},"message":"@ChrisJefferson I think that's a really cool idea. Have you taken a look at how some other tests are written (say in `KeysetTest.cpp` or `main.cpp`, which are usually pretty short functions, which means they're usually simple, tho perhaps shortness doesn't mean that for every test), and had a stab at writing your arithmetic tests?","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1587636422,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDYxODMxMDYwNA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-618310604"},"message":"This is similar to the reversible test, and would need symbolic solver support, like cmbc. I played around with it, but nothing to create useful tests so far. Related to security.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"e225a3173448d545b6be714d2f8e8bafc9d22941"},"timestamp":1599166574,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY4Njc2MDYwMQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-686760601"},"message":"What's the point of a test like this?\nHaving a hash function that satisfies linear relations like what you wrote is actually a great benefit!\nYou can make some really cool algorithms using such functions. See e.g. 2.1 of \"Subquadratic Algorithms for 3SUM\" http://erikdemaine.org/papers/3SUM_WADS2005/paper.pdf","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1599203298,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY4Njk1OTgyMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-686959822"},"message":"Cool properties are not so cool if you can trivially reverse them, or cancel them out as with the CRC family.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"f62b40e67583694618d4db74cb68f583f8560fde"},"timestamp":1599206632,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY4Njk4NzA5Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-686987096"},"message":"In many case, an easy (and fairly good way) of hashing an ordered list is to hash each element, then add the hashes. This actually has provable good properties, as long as your hash function is \"good\", and in this case, satisfying linear relations is the very worst thing.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"e225a3173448d545b6be714d2f8e8bafc9d22941"},"timestamp":1599222809,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY4NzExNDgxMQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/51#issuecomment-687114811"},"message":"If you hash (x,y) as `h(x)+h'(y)` where `h` and `h'` are each 2-independent/universal and independent of each other, then the result is a 2-independent hash of `(x,y)`.\nYou don't need any \"non-linearity\" properties.\nIf `h` and `h'` are the same hash function, no properties can save you from `h(x)+h(x)=2h(x)`.\n\nI guess this all depends on what properties you want from your hash function.\nFor crypto, I'm sure linearity isn't great.\nFor algorithms having a collision-resistant hash function, that's also linear, can be a great thing.\n\nI like that about smhasher, one can get a quick overview of which functions satisfy which properties, and pick the one that suits their use-case. Just don't pretend like all of these \"properties\" are necessarily a bad thing to always be avoided.","files":null}]}